'''Gordon "Gordie" Fashoway''' (born June 16, 1926 in [[Portage la Prairie, Manitoba]]) is a former [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|left winger]]. During the [[1950<U+2013>51 NHL season|1950<U+2013>51 season]], he played in his only 13 [[NHL]] games for the [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]]. 

Following the Black Hawks, Fashoway played for several teams in the [[Western Hockey League (minor pro)|Western Hockey League]]: the [[New Westminster Royals]], [[Victoria Cougars]], and [[Portland Buckaroos]], where he ended his professional career in 1963.

After his playing career he became the head coach of the [[Oakland Seals]] for one year in [[1968<U+2013>69 NHL season|1968]], and then returned to coach the Buckaroos from 1969 to 1973. Under his leadership, the Buckaroos captured their third WCHL championship in the 1970<U+2013>71.<ref name=whl>{{cite web|url=http://www.hockeyleaguehistory.com/Western_Hockey_League_1952.htm|title=Western Hockey League (1952<U+2013>1974)|publisher=HockeyLeagueHistory.com|accessdate=2008-04-18}}</ref>

== Awards and achievements ==
*Turnbull Cup [[MJHL]] Championship (1946)
*[[Memorial Cup]] Championship (1946)
*[[United States Hockey League (1945-1951)|USHL]] First All-Star Team (1950)
*[[PCHL]] First All-Star Team (1952)
*[[Western Hockey League (minor pro)|WHL]] Coast Division Second All-Star Team (1957, 1958, & 1961)
*WHL Championship (1961)
*WHL Championship as coach (1971)
*<U+201C>Honoured Member<U+201D> of the [[Manitoba Hockey Hall of Fame]]

